  "caption": "The weirdest AI attack doesn't get typed into the chat box. It hides in the content your AI agent reads.\n\nThat's indirect prompt injection: instructions tucked into a web page, email, document, or image that the model treats as commands. OWASP's Top 10 for LLM Applications lists prompt injection, sensitive-information disclosure, and excessive agency as core risks — and the danger spikes the moment your agent can act (send mail, read files, call APIs) on what it just read.\n\nDefender move: isolate untrusted content from privileged tools, scope agent permissions to the minimum, log every action, and require human confirmation for sensitive steps.\n\nIf your agent summarizes a random webpage, should it also be allowed to email your team? Where would you draw that line?\n\nFollow for AI security breakdowns without the fake panic.",
  "hashtags": [
    "#Cybersecurity",
    "#AISecurity",
    "#PromptInjection",
    "#LLMSecurity",
    "#AIagents",
    "#AppSec",
    "#OWASP"
  ],
  "comment_prompt": "Would your agent trust a webpage it was told to summarize?",
